---
import BlogArticle from "../../../layouts/BlogArticle.astro";

const title = "What is a .gitignore File";
---

<BlogArticle title={title}>
  <strong class="pub-time">19/07/2022</strong>

  <h2>Description</h2>
  <p>
    A <code>.gitignore</code> file is a file which specifies which files to ignore and include when you are using
    git. It is typically located in the top level working directory of your project, and includes folders such as
    runtime environments, build files, node_modules, and other files that are not part of the project's source code.
  </p>

  <h2>Example</h2>
  <p>An automatically generated <code>.gitignore</code> file by Rust Lang's Cargo package manager</p>
  <div class="code-block container large-container">
    # Generated by Cargo <br>
    # will have compiled files and executables <br>
    debug/ <br>
    target/ <br>
    <br>
    # Remove Cargo.lock from gitignore if creating an executable, leave it for libraries <br>
    # More information here https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/guide/cargo-toml-vs-cargo-lock.html <br>
    Cargo.lock <br>
    <br>
    # These are backup files generated by rustfmt <br>
    **/*.rs.bk <br>
    <br>
    # MSVC Windows builds of rustc generate these, which store debugging information <br>
    *.pdb <br>
  </div>

  <hr>

  <h2>Useful Tools</h2>
  <div>
    <a href="https://github.com/github/gitignore">GitHub collection of pre-made .gitignore files</a><br>
    <a href="https://www.toptal.com/developers/gitignore">Automatic .gitignore creator by toptal</a><br>
  </div>

  <h2>Syntax</h2>
  <div class="container large-container">
    <h3>Comments</h3><br>
    A comment can be used to annotate a <code>.gitignore</code> file, and while not affect the functionality. It is
    typically used to describe the a purpose of a line or statement. <br>

    <div class="indent">
      <b>Usage</b><br>
      <code># this is a comment</code>
      <br>
      <b>Context</b><br>
      <div class="code-block">
        # exclude the node_modules/ directory from git <br>
        node_modules/
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="container large-container">
    <h3>Excluding Folders</h3><br>
    Excluding folders is typically used to exclude runtime environments, and specialty folders such as
    <code>node_modules/</code> and the <code>out/</code> directories. <br>

    <div class="indent">
      <b>Usage</b><br>
      <code>folder_name/</code>
      <br>
      <b>Context</b><br>
      <div class="code-block">
        # exclude the node_modules/ directory from git <br>
        node_modules/
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="container large-container">
    <h3>Excluding Files</h3><br>
    Excluding files is typically used to distribution files, compiled files, temp, cache, secret files, and output
    files as <code>a.out</code>. <br>

    <div class="indent">
      <b>Usage</b><br>
      <code>python_file.py</code>
      <br>
      <b>Context</b><br>
      <div class="code-block">
        # excludes the a.out files from the gcc compiler <br>
        a.out
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="container large-container">
    <h3>Wildcard Expressions</h3><br>
    The use of wildcard expressions is typically used to exclude a specific filetype from git, such as JavaScript
    files in a TypeScript project. <br>

    <div class="indent">
      <b>Usage</b><br>
      <code>*.fileType</code><br>
      <code>**/*.fileType</code>
      <br>
      <b>Context</b><br>
      <div class="code-block">
        # exclude all JavaScript files in the dist/ directory <br>
        dist/*.js <br>
        <br>
        # exclude all .out files from git <br>
        **/*.out <br>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="container large-container">
    <h3>Include</h3><br>
    Including in a <code>.gitignore</code> is typically used when you have excluded an entire directory, but want to
    a limited number of files from this directory. <br>

    <div class="indent">
      <b>Usage</b><br>
      <code>!fileName.py</code><br>
      <code>!folderName/</code>
      <br>
      <b>Context</b><br>
      <div class="code-block">
        # include the javascript files in the dist/ folder <br>
        dist/* <br>
        !dist/*.js <br>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><br>

